post_text:
Good afternoon families,

As we move closer to the start of the 20-21 school year, please know that the entire staff of South Shore Technical is working diligently to provide your child with the best education possible, not matter the scenario we make encounter.

As we begin to put the finishing touches on a school reopening plan that we will share with you in a couple of weeks, we are looking at employing a staggered start to the school day. We are doing this to be able to transport as many students as possible to and from school safely.

We are including in the email you have registered with the school a followup survey on transportation based upon this staggered model. We ask that you please take a moment to answer this 3-question survey so we can make sure we are planning appropriate for your family's needs.

The Leadership Team
South Shore Technical

As this challenging school year draws to a close, I want to thank you all for your flexibility and patience, two habits of mind needed by all of us in these past three months. Amidst our preparations for the reopening of school in September, our school community will also be engaging in dialogue about the distressing racial incidents across our country. South Shore’s school mission statement calls for us to help develop confident, civic-minded students who will make a positive impact on their community. In today’s world, such a mission has never been more important. I would welcome any thoughts or ideas that parents and students may wish to share.

post_text:
Good evening,

As many of you are now aware, Ryan Mahoney, the Senior Class President, was omitted from this evening's presentation. This was simply a human error. We acknowledge and understand that we can not undone the damage and suffering this has done to Ryan and her family, but we will be doing an updated presentation to honor all Ryan has done for our school.

Ryan is truly a leader in every sense of the word. She has not only been a member of the Student Council all four years, but a member of the National Honor Society, SkillsUSA, our Ambassador's program and an athlete. Ryan has been a stalwart at every South Shore event for the past four years. As a member of the School Council and as Senior Class President over the past three months, Ryan has represented her peers impeccably as she has argued for everything the Class of 2020 deserves.

Ryan will be continuing her studies in nursing program upon graduation.

Again, we deeply apologize for this error.

South Shore Technical

post_text:
Good afternoon,

None of us are where we expected to be today. In just a few hours the Class of 2020 was scheduled to graduate in front of family, friends and staff under the tent at the South Shore Music Circus.

A lot has changed over the past three months, but what hasn't changed is our desire to honor the Class of 2020 and all they have accomplished. To this end, with the help of some of those same family and friends, South Shore will be premiering at 6:00 pm this evening a presentation that honors all 143 members of the Class of 2020.

This presentation encapsulates who the Class of 2020 were, what they've accomplished and where they are going. Be on the lookout for hidden surprises including vocational shop awards and scholarships. To view this presentation please visit the school website, www.ssvotech.org.

Our graduation ceremony is still scheduled for 10:00 AM on Saturday, June 27th.

Sincerely,
South Shore Administration

post_text:
Good evening,

This week will mark the last scheduled academic cycle for the Class of 2020. Congratulations!

After this Thursday, teachers will be recording grades based upon the work seniors have done during the remote learning school, April 6th thru May 21st. This grade will count as 20% of your overall grade, and will be combined with the grade you earned in school through March 13th, which will count as 80% of your grade. This combined grade will be used to determine if the students has passed the course for the school year.

Students whose combined grade does not meet South Shore's standard of a 65 to pass a course will be required to continue working after the class is complete in order to meet the standard expected by the school district. Students will need to passes all their courses in order to earn a diploma.

Thank you and enjoy your week!

The Leadership Team

post_text: On Friday, South Shore Tech will help feed hundreds of Marshfield Families through a combined effort with the Marshfield Food Pantry and The Marshfield Boys and Girls Club. Julie Johnson, Marshfield Food Pantry Treasurer and Marshfield Boys and Girls Club CEO Jim Bunnell have been working together giving meals to over 260 families 3 times per week between the two locations. Thanks to the Chef’s at South Shore Tech, Friday afternoon, starting at 4:00 families will be able to pick up heat and eat options such as Turkey or Beef Meatballs in Marinara, Pasta tossed in Marinara , Sliced Corned beef and potatoes. As well as bags of dinner rolls. The Marshfield Food Pantry will also be able to store and bake as needed assorted cookie dough scoops for their community. This opportunity would not have been possible without the support of The Marshfield Public Schools, The Marshfield Education Foundation, and Sewing Seed of Marshfield.

We wanted to remind everyone that our Remote Learning School begins week 2 at 10:00 am tomorrow morning. Freshmen and Juniors will be in academics while sophomores and seniors will move to shop and related. You will find copies of this week's schedule and an agenda page to help students stay on track with deadlines in your school email.

As always students should fill out the attendance survey to start their day. On Monday, you will hear a personal message from Mr. Aubrey.

Finally, The Department of Education has allowed and our own School Committee has voted to not have April Vacation this year. We have chosen to do this to keep momentum going for our Remote Learning School. Therefore, B cycle academic, shop and related classes will run Tuesday through Friday next week. This change will move the last day of school to Friday, June 12th. We will share a new school calendar with you later in the week.

As always stay safe, stay mentally engaged and be physically active.

The Leadership Team

post_text:
Hello South Shore Tech Families & Staff,

This is Superintendent Tom Hickey writing to inform you that, after consultation with Massachusetts Department of Public Health, Department of Elementary and Secondary Education and area school districts, South Shore Tech will close for the next two weeks, reopening March 30, 2020.

While there are no active COVID-19 cases in our school, this is being done with an abundance of caution. I would encourage you to check your email and school website this afternoon for a more detailed letter from me on this topic.

We appreciate everyone's patience and understanding during this unsettled time.
We will be available to communicate with families during the closure if the need should arise.

Thank you.
text:
Hello South Shore Tech Families & Staff,

This is Superintendent Tom Hickey writing to inform you that, after consultation with Massachusetts Department of Public Health, Department of Elementary and Secondary Education and area school districts, South Shore Tech will close for the next two weeks, reopening March 30, 2020.

While there are no active COVID-19 cases in our school, this is being done with an abundance of caution. I would encourage you to check your email and school website this afternoon for a more detailed letter from me on this topic.

We appreciate everyone's patience and understanding during this unsettled time.
We will be available to communicate with families during the closure if the need should arise.

Thank you.

Let's "White Out" the gym in support of our teams!

Tickets for entry to both games: $5 per adult and $3 per student.

post_text:
Hello,

We wanted to let you know that we are closing out the winter sport season, which means that senior nights are upon us. The first will be held tomorrow as our swim team will be celebrating our seniors at the All League Championship.

The meet will be held at the Burkland School, 41 Mayflower Ave, Middlebrough MA.

The schedule of events.

Senior Recognition will be at 9:45
National Anthem at 9:55
Meet start at 10:05

Parents/families there will be admission charged to cover league costs for the meet- $5 adults/students and if you want a program it'll be $2. Please bring cash
There is a concession stand run by the Middleboro parents with food and beverages for sale throughout the meet- again cash only.

post_text:
Good afternoon,

Just a reminder that tomorrow evening South Shore Tech will be holding its 3rd annual Comedy Night fundraiser to support our SkillsUSA Chapter at the school. SkillsUSA is a program that allows students to compete in trade specific and project-based competitions against students from other vocational schools in the region, the state and nationally.

Tomorrow's comedy night will be held at Venus III in Hanson. Doors open at 6:30 pm with the show beginning at 8:00 pm. Tickets are $25 and include pizza. A cash bar will also be available.

We hope you can join us for a warm night of laughs with our South Shore family.

Good Afternoon,

A few of holiday reminders from SST

The Horticulture/Landscape Construction Program at SST is selling floral arrangements for the holiday. We currently have 20 arrangements still available! Please visit www.ssvotech.org/flower-shop/ to pre order. Sale ends Thursday 12/19/19 at 1pm. Pick-up will be between the hours of 10am-1pm at the Brass Lantern Restaurant on Thursday 12/19/19. We appreciate the support for our program, and Happy Holidays!

* PS - Santa Paws arrangement is sold out.

The Parent's Association and Viking Athletic Association will be back in the school tonight and Friday night from 6:00 to 8:00 pm with South Shore Tech gear for sale.

Finally, this Friday, December 20th, is the last day of school this calendar year. We will see everyone on January 2nd, 2020.

post_url:
The soccer team beat Westport High School today 2-1 in the MIAA tournament. This is the first MIAA tournament victory in at least 30 years! Trailing 1-0, Ryder Nilson blasted a 35 yard direct kick into the upper right corner to tie the game. The Vikings then controlled play throughout the second half but neither team could score.
Outstanding goal keeping by Noah Sinatra who shut out Westport during two overtime periods leading to a penalty kick situation, where the Vikings prevailed 3-1 in penalty kicks and earned the victory. Sinatra not only stopped three penalty shots as goalie, he scored one of our goals. The team plays next at Cohasset, Thursday (time TBA).
